  "prompt": "What is the best way to simplify [math]\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}[/math] where defined?",
  "response": "Let's solve this step by step:\n\n1) First, let's clarify where the expression is defined\n   \u2022 The expression is defined for all x except x = 0\n   \u2022 This is because division by zero would be undefined\n\n2) To simplify this, we can find a common denominator in the numerator and denominator\n\n3) In the numerator, we have [math]x - \\frac{1}{x}[/math]\n   \u2022 To get a common denominator, multiply by [math]\\frac{x}{x}[/math]\n   \u2022 [math]x - \\frac{1}{x} = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x}[/math]\n\n4) In the denominator, we have [math]1 + \\frac{1}{x}[/math]\n   \u2022 To get a common denominator, multiply by [math]\\frac{x}{x}[/math]\n   \u2022 [math]1 + \\frac{1}{x} = \\frac{x + 1}{x}[/math]\n\n5) Now our expression looks like: [math]\\frac{\\frac{x^2 - 1}{x}}{\\frac{x + 1}{x}}[/math]\n\n6) When dividing fractions, we multiply by the reciprocal\n   \u2022 [math]\\frac{x^2 - 1}{x} \\cdot \\frac{x}{x + 1}[/math]\n\n7) Simplify: [math]\\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}[/math]\n\n8) Factor the numerator: [math]\\frac{(x+1)(x-1)}{x + 1}[/math]\n\n9) Cancel: [math]x - 1[/math]\n\nTherefore, [math]\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}} = x - 1[/math], where defined.\n\nThe answer is [math]x - 1[/math].",
